solution.p:
(d) To find  p_2 we can apply Bernoulli's equation between 0 and 2 or 1 and 2.  We will use 1 and 2 pair.

	p_2 + \dfrac{1}{2}\rho v_2^2 + \rho g h_2 = p_1 + \dfrac{1}{2}\rho v_1^2 + \rho g h_1. 

In this equation we already know the following.

	 \amp  h_1 = 0 
	 \amp  v_1 = 3.13 \ \text{m/s}
	\amp  p_1 = p_{\text{atm}} = 1.013 \times 10^{5}\ \text{Pa}
	\amp  h_2 = 0.3\ \text{m}
	\amp  v_2 = 0.125\ \text{m/s} 

Putting these values we solve for  p_2.

p_2 =  p_{\text{atm}} - 2450\ \text{Pa}.

At the critical height h_c we will have the following values.

	 \amp  h_1 = 0,
	 \amp  v_1 = 0\ \ \textrm{(just when starts to flow)}
	 \amp  p_1 = p_{\textrm{atm}} = 1.013 \times 10^{5}\ \textrm{Pa}
	 \amp  h_2 =  h_c\ \ \textrm{(the critical height)}
	 \amp  v_2 = 0.

This gives

	\rho g h_c = p_{\textrm{atm}}.

Therefore

	h_c = \frac{p_{\textrm{atm}}}{\rho g} = 10.34\ \textrm{m}.
